    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and im kinda confused. i feel like i'm paying a lot every month but the actual amount i owe isnt going down as much as i thought it would. can u explain how the interest actually works with the payments? why does it seem like so much of my money is just disappearing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, let's break it down. Student loans typically have a combination of interest and principal (the actual loan amount). When you make a payment, a larger portion initially goes towards the interest, especially if your loan has a fixed interest rate. This means part of your payment is essentially not reducing the principal, which is why it may feel like little of your money is going toward the loan itself. However, interest does decrease over time as the principal is paid down, so you will gradually see your payments go mostly toward the principal as you continue to make them.",
