    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i see. so it's basically a cycle where the interest just keeps biting into my payment before it can even touch the debt. it feels like there's this hidden drain constantly pulling money away. if i wanted to see exactly how much interest is being added versus how much principal i'm actually clearing, what kind of math or tool should i be looking at to track that more clearly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To get a clearer picture of how your payment is distributed between interest and principal, you should check your loan statement or borrower's online portal often provided by your loan servicer for a breakdown of payments received, amounts applied to principal, interest, and when your loan is paid out. Some loans offer tools within these platforms to show you a more detailed amortization schedule. An amortization schedule will outline each payment and indicate how much goes towards interest and how much is going towards reducing the principal over the life of your loan. Additionally, using a loan calculator can help model different repayment scenarios to show you how payments might shift over time between principal and interest. Remember, the longer the term and the higher the interest rate, the more you will have interest and less principal initially. However, as each payment is made, the interest portion decreases, gradually allowing more of your payment to go towards the principal.",
      "source": "target",
